n early Christianity, Judaism and Islam, but also positions taken by mediaeval Indian theologians and in the influential traditions of early Buddhism. Traditionally, discussions have focused on questions such as whether time is a necessary concomitant of God’s existence, or whether time should be identified with God. But there is a further question: did these traditions develop their own unrelated and independent view of God and time? Or are there similarities in their reflections? This volume, with contributions of scholars from various relevant fields, offers a novel approach to these inquiries. When taken as a whole, it provides new momentum to contemplation on an age-old enigma.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 4aEwigkeit. 4aGott. 4aKontinuität. 4aVergänglichkeit. 7aRELIGION / Philosophy.2bisacsh  aContinuity.  aEternity.  aGod.  aMomentariness.1 aFischer, Florian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFischer, Florian, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGrössl, Johannes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoover, Jon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMullins, R.T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSakai, Masamichi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSaudek, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchmücker, Marcus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchmücker, Marcus, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSchulz, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStrauss, Ze’ev, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilliams, Michael T., econtributor.4ctb4https